		<header>
			
			<h1>Ghana’s poultry sector continues to struggle despite rise in import prices </h1>

			
			<h4>
												23 September 2013
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>According to its report on Ghana’s poultry sector published in August 2013, USDA is projecting a 5% increase in Ghanaian poultry meat imports in marketing year (MY) 2013, taking these to 165,000 tonnes. USDA reports that “Ghana poultry imports have more than quadrupled since 2002”, adding that the country’s domestic poultry sector has been in decline, meeting “only about 10 percent of total poultry demand in the country”. While traditionally the US was the major supplier of poultry meat to Ghana, in recent years the US share of imports has fallen from 50% in 2003 to 31% in 2012, with the EU and Brazil now playing a larger role. This is attributed to the more attractive appearance of EU and Brazilian poultry cuts and the larger sizes, which are more attractive to the catering trade, since US poultry enjoys a price advantage (the US price is US$2.2/kg, that of the EU US$3.2/kg and that of Brazil US$3.4/kg). Some 80% of imports are frozen poultry parts and 20% are frozen whole chickens.</p><p>Ghana produces around 10,000 tonnes of broiler chickens and 12,400 tonnes of spent layers per year. The low level of production is attributed to “the high cost of production (feed, drugs), inefficient production methods, limited knowledge of modern poultry management, and lack of processing facilities”, as well as high energy costs. According to USDA, “imported poultry products tend to be 30-40 percent cheaper than locally produced chicken.” Controlling animal feed costs is critical to the future of the Ghanaian poultry industry, since these represent 82% of variable production costs. The report notes that costs have been rising in response to rising global maize costs.</p><p>According to USDA’s analysis, the 15 local commercial feed mills operate at only around 40–50% capacity, producing around 100,000 tonnes of compound feed annually.</p><p>The report notes that current Ghanaian government support measures include “removing customs duties on poultry inputs (feed, additives, drugs and vaccines) and facilitating improved access to veterinary services”. In terms of trade policy, poultry imports attract a 20% duty, with an additional 12.5% VAT being levied and other additional charges amounting to about 4.9%.</p><p>Ghanaian per capita poultry consumption is estimated to have increased from 4 kg to 6.6 kg between 2010 and 2012, with a further increase to 6.8 kg projected for 2013. Consumption is heavily weighted towards imports of frozen poultry products, which are cheaper than locally produced chicken. Imports are also more conveniently prepared and packaged and are favoured by the fast food and restaurant trade. In view of these factors, USDA projects a national consumption level of 175,000 tonnes in MY 2013. However, the report notes also that prices of imported chicken are rising from US$1.84–2.36 in 2012 to US$2.63–3.42 in 2013 (an average increase of 44%).</p><p>In terms of processing, there are only limited facilities that prepare quick and easy poultry meat products, and in recent years Ghanaian poultry farmers have focused on egg production. Most large-scale poultry farms have their own bio-security measures, but bio-security tends to be minimal among medium and small-scale operators.</p><p><b>Ghanaian broiler meat production: Consumption and imports 2011–13 (tonnes)</b></p><table class="renderedtable" border="1" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0">
<tr>
